Note on subprocessing: the forking itself is not _that_ bad. I can batch `vfork`/`exec` with throughput 9200 Hz on my laptop.  With ~one subprocess per repo commit, that makes ~3s overhead for tensorflow/tensorflow (29K commits) and ~5s overhead for git/git (50K commits).

<details>

```c
#include <sys/types.h>
#include <sys/wait.h>
#include <unistd.h>

int main() {
    /* Runtime: 1m53.459s = 113.459s = 0.1082 ms/op */
    /* When unbatched: 0.2122ms/op */
    for (size_t i = 0; i < 1024; i++) {
        pid_t pids[1024];
        for (size_t j = 0; j < 1024; j++) {
            pid_t pid = vfork();
            if (!pid) {
                execl("/bin/true", "/bin/true", NULL);
            }
            pids[j] = pid;
        }
        for (size_t j = 0; j < 1024; j++) {
            waitpid(pids[j], NULL, 0);
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```
</details>

Its still possible that a subprocess-based solution could be significantly slower, though, because the subprocesses cant share memory, state, or work.

