An initial technical assessment of which type system is better for us,
disregarding any costs of integration, performance, etc.

The TypeScript playground is at: http://www.typescriptlang.org/play/

Summary
=======

Roughly equivalent:
  - discriminated unions
  - exact and read-only objects
  - object and array type destruction
  - opaque types (via a workaround)
  - upward propagation of constraints

TypeScript better than Flow:
  - checked downcasts

TypeScript worse than Flow:
  - nominal types
  - read-only arrays?
  - variance (unquestionably, fundamentally broken)

Notes:
  - functions are bivariant by default (!!!), but this can be turned off
  - first-class `enum`s have nontrivial runtime elision

Roughly equivalent
==================

Discriminated unions
--------------------

These work exactly as in Flow, as far as I can tell.

Exact and read-only objects
---------------------------

Object types are exact by default. Attributes can be marked `readonly`:

```typescript
type O = { readonly x: number };
const tooMany: O = { x: 1, y: 2 };  // error
const okay: O = { x: 1 };
okay.x++;  // error
```

Object and array type destruction
---------------------------------

Works, with specialized (and cleaner) syntax. For objects:

```typescript
type O = { x: number };
function takesNumber(n: O["x"]) {
    console.log(n.toFixed(3));
}
takesNumber(3.14159265358979);  // okay
takesNumber("three");  // error
```

For arrays:

```typescript
type O = number[];
function takesNumber(n: O[number]) {
    console.log(n.toFixed(3));
}
takesNumber(3.14159265358979);  // okay
takesNumber("three");  // error
```

Opaque types
------------

Not supported directly. The following should be a workaround:

```typescript
declare const NodeAddressIdentity: unique symbol;
export type NodeAddress = typeof NodeAddressIdentity & string;
function nodeAddress(value: string): NodeAddress {
  return value as any;
}
```

This is because TypeScript knows about symbols and supports generative
unique types for them.

[opaque-1]: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/202#issuecomment-381437628
[opaque-2]: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/202#issuecomment-381603738

Upward propagation of constraints
---------------------------------

Not supported (as with Flow):

```typescript
type Foo = { type: "FOO", address: { type: "FOO" }, foo: string };
type Bar = { type: "BAR", address: { type: "BAR" }, bar: string };
type FooBar = Foo | Bar;
function onType(x: FooBar): string {
    return x.type === "FOO" ? x.foo : x.bar;  // works
}
function onAddressType(x: FooBar): string {
    return x.address.type === "FOO" ? x.foo : x.bar;  // error
}
```

TypeScript better than Flow
===========================

Checked downcasts
-----------------

Supported via `as`:

```typescript
const x: number = 3;
const a: 3 = x;  // fails, as expected
const b: 3 = x as 3;  // works!
const c: string = a as string;  // fails! 'number' not subtype of 'string'
```

TypeScript worse than Flow
==========================

Nominal types
-------------

Explicitly opaque types are not supported, and furthermore classes are
treated as structural:

```typescript
class FileSystem {
    close(fd: number): boolean {
        console.log("Closing file...");
        return true;  // success!
    }
}

class ApproximateNumber {
    close(x: number): boolean {
        const closeEnough = Math.abs(x) < 1e-6;
        return closeEnough;
    }
}

function closeStdout(fs: FileSystem) {
    fs.close(1);
}

declare const z: ApproximateNumber;
closeStdout(z);  // no error! bad! :o
```

Read-only arrays
----------------

Theres a generic `Readonly` type, but it doesnt seem to be very
useful:

```typescript
declare let x: Readonly<number>;
x++;  // no error!

declare const xs: Readonly<number[]>;
xs[0] = 3;  // error
xs.push(3);  // no error!
xs.reverse();  // no error!
```

Variance
--------

Variance annotations not supported. Apparently, all generic types are
treated as bivariant, which is completely broken:

```typescript
declare class Container<T> {
    put(t: T): void;
    getAll(): T[];
};

class Animal {
    speak() {
        console.log("hello");
    }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    speak() {
        console.log("woof");
    }
    shout() {
        console.log("arf arf arf");
    }
}

declare function f(x: Container<Animal>): void;

declare const animals: Container<Animal>;
declare const dogs: Container<Dog>;
declare const strings: Container<string>;

f(animals);  // works (good)
f(dogs);     // works!!! :o (very bad)
f(strings);  // fails (good)
```

Here's a proposal on weight function semantics.

Let a weight function map from a subset of nodes in the graph to real numbers,
where for each node `n`, `W(n)` represents the logarithm of the relative
significance of that node. For example, suppose we have a graph with the
following nodes:

- `r`: SourceCred repository
- `p1`, `p2`: pull requests
- `i1`: an issue
- `c1`, `c2`, `c3`, `c4`: commits

One example of a weight function is `w`, a prior over node types, defined as
follows. (I use base two logarithms due to personal preference.)

```
w(r) = 1
w(p1, p2) = 0
w(i1) = -1
w(c1, c2, c3, c4) = -2
```

This expreses that repositories are twice as important as pulls, which are
twice as important as issues, which are twice as important as commits.
Obviously, this is equivalent to another weight function, `w'`, defined as
follows:

```
w'(r) = 0
w'(p1, p2) = -1
w'(i1) = -2
w'(c1, c2, c3, c4) = -3
```

Within this equivalence class, let's consider "canonical" the weight function
which sums to 0, which in this case is 

```
w_c(r) = 2
w_c(p1, p2) = 1
w_c(i1) =  0
w_c(c1, c2, c3, c4) = -1
```

Now let's consider another weight function, this time defined only over the pull requests.
Perhaps it is counting the lines of code, so we can call it `loc`.

```
loc(p1) = 1
loc(p2) = 0
```

This expresses that p1 is twice as important as p2. However, it is not
meaningfully defined over all of the nodes in the graph. It might seem natural
to pad the remaining entries with zero, but this makes equivalent relative
weightings of pulls no longer equivalent in how they modify the whole graph.
Consider the functions `loc'` and `loc''`

```

loc'(p1) = 1
loc'(p2) = 0
loc'(r, i1, c1, c2, c3, c4) = 0


loc''(p1) = 0
loc''(p2) = -1
loc''(r1, i1, c1, c2, c3, c4) = 0
```

Even though `loc'` and `loc''` are expressing the same relative weightings
between pull requests, `loc'` also shifts overall weight in the graph towards
pull requests in general, while `loc''` shifts overall weight in the graph away
from pull requests. This is an unwanted side effect. Therefore, I think it
makes more sense for weighting functions only to be defined for the subset of
nodes that they explicitly compare. We can then define a function
`normalize` which turns the weighting into a canonical weight distribution via
the following procedure:

```javascript
type LogWeight = number;
// Not guaranteed to have every node in the graph. Not normalized
type Weighting = Map<NodeAddressT, LogWeight>;

// Guaranteed to have every node in the graph, and is normalized.
type NormalizedWeighting = Map<NodeAddressT, LogWeight>;

normalize(graph: Graph, weighting: Weighting): NormalizedWeighting
  let totalWeight = 0;
  let numWeights = 0;
  for (const weight of weighting.values()) {
    totalWeight += weight;
    numWeights++;
  }
  const normalizer = totalWeight / numWeights;
  const normWeighting: NormalizedWeighting = new Map();
  for (const node of graph.nodes()) {
    const w = weighting.get(node);
    normWeighting.set(node, w == null ? 0 : w - normalizer)
  }
  return normWeighting;
```

This has the advantage that it makes it easy to specify relative comparisons between
different nodestypes in easy-to-grok units (a is 2x as important as b), without accidentally
shifting the distribution over nodes that are out of scope for that weighting.

To round things out, here are psuedocode implementations of the three types of
weight functions described above.


```javascript

### Prior over types

const typeToWeight = {
  GitHub.Repo: 5,
  GitHub.User: 3,
  GitHub.Pull: 2,
  GitHub.Issue: 1,
  GitHub.Review: 0,
  GitHub.Comment: -1,
  Git.Commit: 0,
  Git.Tree: -4,
  Git.Blob: -5,
  Git.TreeEntry: -5,
}

const typeWeight = (n: NodeAddressT) => {
  return typeToWeight[getType(n)]
}

### Domain specific comparison

const locWeight = (n: NodeAddressT) => {
  if (getType(n) === GitHub.Pull) {
    const pull = githubRelationalView.get(n);
    const weight = Math.log(pull.additions() + pull.deletions);
    return weight;
  }
  return undefined;
}


### Subproject comparison

const canonicalBackendNodes = new Set([
  // list of nodes, as voted on by users or created via TCR or 
  // some other mechanism
])

const backendWeight = (n: NodeAddressT) => {
  if (canonicalBackendNodes.has(n)) {
  if (canonicalBackendNodes.has(n)) {
    return 4; // tunable parameter
  } else {
    return 0;
  }
}
```

