Ive rewritten the invariants to make them clearer. Ive reduce the use
of TFAEs, which I think have introduced some subtleties. Now, we have
one invariant for each property of the class, describing what it is that
an element of that property implies about other elements and properties.
This also lends itself to a nice implementation.

Here are the new proposed invariants:

```js
  // Definition. A node `n` is in the graph if `_nodes.has(n)`.
  //
  // Definition. An edge `e` is in the graph if `_edges.has(e.address)`.
  //
  // Definition. A *logical value* is an equivalence class of ECMAScript
  // values modulo deep equality (or, from context, an element of such a
  // class).
  //
  // Invariant 1. For a node `n`, if `n` is in the graph, then
  // `_inEdges.has(n)` and `_outEdges.has(n)`.
  //
  // Invariant 2. For an edge `e`, if `e` is in the graph, then:
  //  1. `e.src` is in the graph;
  //  2. `e.dst` is in the graph;
  //  3. `edges.get(e.address)` is deep-equal to `e`;
  //  4. `_inEdges.get(e.dst)` contains `e`; and
  //  5. `_outEdges.get(e.src)` contains `e`.
  //
  // Invariant 3. Suppose that `_inEdges.has(n)` and, let `es` be
  // `_inEdges.get(n)`. Then
  //  1. `n` is in the graph;
  //  2. `es` contains any logical value at most once;
  //  3. if `es` contains `e`, then `e` is in the graph; and
  //  4. if `es` contains `e`, then `e.dst === n`.
  //
  // Invariant 4. Suppose that `_outEdges.has(n)` and, let `es` be
  // `_outEdges.get(n)`. Then
  //  1. `n` is in the graph;
  //  2. `es` contains any logical value at most once;
  //  3. if `es` contains `e`, then `e` is in the graph; and
  //  4. if `es` contains `e`, then `e.src === n`.
```

